<br>
And YOU need to take a look at some facts.  These laws and regulations are often extremely old, in some cases pre-dateing even the formation of the United States.  The Temperence movement that eventually led to Prohibition started in earnest in the early 1800's.  A lot of these laws were the result of campaigns by those temperance movements on a local level.  These Temperance movements were first started and gained there biggest support from religous organizations.   One thing must be said though.  Some of the laws were passed pre-14th Admendment.  Prior to the 14th Admendment The Federal Bill of Rights did not apply to State laws.   State Laws only had to abide by thier own constitutions so these older laws were perfectly alright when they were first passed.<br>
<br>
I have no problem with the general regualtions.  It is the treating of &quot;Sunday&quot; as different that is the problem.   There is no secular reason to treat Sunday as different.   Unless you can show me a reason WHY Suday is different that has nothing to do with religon, the governement has no place dictating the religous standards(Sunday being special) of the majority on everyone.  <br>
<br>
These laws DO get challanged, it has happened a lot here in Ohio.  They almost never get to actual court because the Government(state or local) usually caves before it gets too far.  As a result over the last 10 years the regulations that treated Sunday as &quot;different&quot; from other days of the week have all but disappeared.  <br>
